page.title: 07WALK IN WYDALE, SNAINTON
page.content: It was a lovely spring morning.The first tree we see was an oak which had a yellow honey fungus on it and around the fungus the branches were dead. The oak has distinctive wobbly-like leaves. Then Andrew spotted a thistle covered with cuckoo spit with a tiny frog hopper in the spit. The first flower we found was a bird's foot trefoil_it has over 70 names including 'bacon and eggs'! I picked some dog and briar roses; dog roses are whitey pink and briar roses pinky red. At the end of the path was the quarry and then the Beech wood.We walked on the beech mast,when that rots it leaves an acidy soil that most plants and trees don't like, nettles grow, but not very well.We saw an elm with Dutch Elm disease.
